--- body ---
## Context

Audit 0070 identified bias **B2** (retro-indexing of the pre-DOI era) as
a ❌ gap: OpenAlex and similar sources add pre-2000 records post-hoc as
third-party metadata improves. A 1995 slice of the corpus queried in 2026
is structurally different from a 1995 slice queried in 1995 or 2010. Our
periodization places Act I at 1990-2006 — that's the window most exposed
to retro-indexing artifacts.

## Actions

1. For each record in `refined_works`, extract the first-indexed date
   from OpenAlex (field `created_date` or equivalent) vs `publication_year`.
2. Compute the per-year distribution of record-age at first indexing
   (indexed_year − publication_year). Plot it.
3. Report the share of pre-2005 records first indexed after 2010 (proxy
   for "found via later metadata enrichment"). If the share is > 10% per
   year, the pre-2005 slice is materially skewed.
4. If material, prototype a filter: `include only records first indexed
   before publication_year + N years`. Re-run the divergence pipeline on
   the filtered corpus. Report whether the 2007 transition zone shifts.
5. Deliverable: one supplementary figure + a paragraph for §6.4.

## Test

Start with:
`tests/test_retro_indexing.py::test_indexed_date_field_present` — asserts
the enriched_works schema exposes an indexed/created timestamp per
record. Red until the enrichment step surfaces it.

## Exit criteria

- A supplementary figure of record-age-at-indexing distribution by
  publication year.
- A §6.4 paragraph (≤ 80 words) quantifying the bias magnitude and
  stating whether it changes the Act I narrative.
- If magnitude is material, a merged PR that exposes an optional filter.
